39:16.340 --> 39:20.660
But a unistochastic probability matrix is vastly deeper.

39:20.660 --> 39:32.160
It means those final positive probabilities are actually generated by taking a deeper matrix of complex numbers, a unitary matrix, and squaring their absolute values.

39:32.280 --> 39:35.980
And why does introducing complex numbers completely change the physics?

39:36.160 --> 39:40.560
Because complex numbers possess a property that real numbers do not.

39:40.840 --> 39:41.880
They have a phase.

39:41.980 --> 39:42.900
They have an angle.

39:43.160 --> 39:43.620
An angle.

39:44.160 --> 39:44.800
Like an arrow.

39:45.140 --> 39:48.480
Think of them exactly like tiny arrows pointing in different directions.

39:48.480 --> 39:53.120
In classical probability, 10% plus 10% is always 20%.

39:53.120 --> 40:02.780
But when you deal with complex amplitudes, if one arrow points up and the other arrow points down, they can actually cancel each other out to zero.

40:03.080 --> 40:05.920
Or if they point the same way, they can amplify each other.

40:06.480 --> 40:13.820
This is the phenomenon of interference, and it is the absolute defining hallmark of quantum mechanics.

40:13.820 --> 40:21.100
Okay, so we have these localized, unistochastic patches of reality governed by complex phases.

